%#############################################################
\chapter{Households}
\label{chap:households} \index{households}
%#############################################################
\epigraph{There is nothing like staying at home for real comfort.}{Austen, Jane} 

Equation \ref{eq:IPARX} and Chapters~\ref{chap:introduction}--\ref{chap:impact_intensity}
developed a framework for sustainability thinking. 
This chapter is the first of four chapters to apply that framework to some
areas of life where sustainability challenges\index{sustainability challenges}
are relevant and important. 
The areas are selected based, in part, on where energy
is consumed (Figure \ref{fig:LLNL_energy_sankey}), that is, 
the drivers of carbon emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!household} (Table \ref{tab:corrected_co2_emissions}).
This chapter (Chapter~\ref{chap:households}) explores 
implications and applications of sustainability thinking
to households.
Transportation (Chapter~\ref{chap:transportation}), 
agriculture (Chapter~\ref{chap:agriculture}), and
land use %and urban planning\index{urban planning} 
(Chapter~\ref{chap:land_use_urban_planning})
are the subjects of the next three chapters.
The structure of each chapter in Part \ref{part:sustainability_challenges} is similar:
First, quantity and sources of demand in that particular area are discussed.
Next, sustainability challenges in that area are examined.
Finally, routes for a transition to a more-sustainable world are considered.

The topic of this chapter, households,
is important for sustainability and stands in contrast to 
the formal employment sector.
With the exception of 
physical plant employees, building managers, and custodial staff, 
few workers 
make decisions about buildings and machines
that affect energy and material resource consumption in offices and factories.

Although ordinary people often have little power to make decisions
with sustainability implications
at work, at school, or at church,
everyone who lives in (or works from) 
a house or apartment 
makes decisions with sustainability implications
in their own household.
Indeed, households are the site for decisions about consumption of 
food, water, material, and energy.

%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth)
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
In households, sustainability meets everyday life.
\end{mcframe}

We use the term ``household'' to indicate both 
a single housing unit (or dwelling) and
the people who live in it (occupants).
A housing unit is the structure and its systems, 
either a detached home, an apartment unit, or a townhouse.
When we say that households are important for sustainability, 
we are referring to the structure of the housing unit
(roof, walls, and floors), 
the systems in it the housing unit
(heating\index{heating system}, cooling\index{cooling system}, and water, for example), and 
the decisions made by the occupants.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Demand for energy in households}
\label{sec:energy_demand_households}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Many resources are demanded by households, 
both the people who occupy a dwelling and 
the systems that operate within the dwelling. 
Example resources demanded by households include
water, building materials, chemicals, food,
electricity\index{electricity}, and natural gas\index{natural gas}.
Each resource demanded by households is an
entry in the list of resources in the numerator of the
\mft{R} term of the IPARX identity\index{IPARX identity} (Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}). 
This chapter focuses on demand for energy in households, 
in keeping with the prime example of the book,
energy consumption and carbon emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions}. 

Dwellings are important for sustainability, 
in part because they are sites of energy consumption.
For example, Figure~\ref{fig:LLNL_energy_sankey} shows that 
11.9~quads of final energy\index{final energy} were consumed in U.S.\ residences in 2018,
representing 12\% of final energy\index{final energy} consumption.
Table~\ref{tab:corrected_co2_emissions} shows that CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!household}
from the U.S.\ residential sector in 2018 total 
\Sexpr{US_CO2_by_sector$`CO$_2$ emissions [Mt]`[[1]] %>% round(0)}~Mt/year,
predominantly from electricity\index{electricity} and natural gas\index{natural gas}.
Energy consumption in dwellings is a source of sustainability impacts
(CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!household} and 
natural resource extraction\index{resource extraction})
far beyond the site of the demand.
Thus, decisions made by households have sustainability implications
far beyond the walls of each abode.

Total U.S.\ energy consumption by households 
has been climbing slowly since the 1970s; 
see Figure~\ref{fig:TotalHouseholdEnergyConsumption}.
Increasing energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency} of appliances and improvements to building envelopes 
(roof, walls, windows\index{window}, and base of a dwelling)
have decreased the energy consumption per housing unit;
see Figure~\ref{fig:AverageHouseholdEnergyConsumption}.
But the number of housing units is rising.


