Guided by the aggregation above,
this section focuses attention on four important drivers for 
household energy consumption and CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!household}:
(a)~size and location,
(b)~heating\index{space heating} and cooling\index{space cooling},
(c)~hygiene\index{hygiene}, and
(d)~lighting\index{lighting}.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Size and location}
\label{sec:size_and_location}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Both size and location are important drivers for household energy use.

%..............................
\paragraph{Size} 
\label{sec:dwelling_size} \index{households!size}
%..............................

Figure~\ref{fig:NewHousingSize} shows the average floor space \index{households!floor space}
of new single-family homes in the United States between 1971 and 2019.
The general trend is toward larger homes over time, with recent declines.
Figure~\ref{fig:EnergyConsAndHomeSize} shows that
energy consumption increases with home size.\index{households!energy consumption}
Figure~\ref{fig:PersonsPerHousehold} 
shows that the number of occupants per dwelling
is falling over time.

Taken together, Figures~\ref{fig:NewHousingSize} and~\ref{fig:EnergyConsAndHomeSize}
would suggest that residential energy consumption per dwelling is rising through time.
However, Figure~\ref{fig:AverageHouseholdEnergyConsumption} shows that
per-household energy consumption is falling over time.
Improved insulation\index{insulation} and 
higher system efficiencies (furnaces and other appliances)
are reducing energy consumption per housing unit, 
despite increasing size.
That said, more homes with fewer occupants are driving the total U.S.\
household energy consumption up slightly from 1970--today; 
see Figure~\ref{fig:TotalHouseholdEnergyConsumption}.


