From a sustainability point of view,
smaller, more-efficient homes with more occupants
are preferred.
However, trends suggest that although homes are becoming more efficient,
there are more of them, 
they are becoming larger, and
they have fewer occupants on average.


%..............................
\paragraph{Location} 
\label{sec:dwelling_location} \index{households!location}
%..............................

Location of a dwelling is also an important determiner of energy consumption,
not just for the dwelling itself, but also for energy consumed by the residents
for transportation.
(See Chapter~\ref{chap:transportation} for more information on sustainability issues
related to transportation.)
Proximity to work, school, shops, church, and entertainment
makes a significant difference to transportation energy demand.
When buying a home, some purchasers can choose among 
urban, suburban, and rural locations, 
with important sustainability implications.
Living in an urban center can reduce average transportation distances. 
Living in the suburbs or in rural areas can mean
increased fuel use and CO$_2$ emissions for transportation\index{CO$_2$ emissions!transportation}. 

Zooming out, the latitude of the home may make a 
larger impact on household sustainability
than urban, suburban, or rural location.
Homes at high latitudes require heating. 
Homes at low latitudes are often fitted with air-conditioning\index{air-conditioning}.
Both heating and air-conditioning\index{air-conditioning} require energy and, 
in today's fossil-fuel-powered world,
cause CO$_2$ to be emitted;
see Section~\ref{sec:heating_and_cooling}.
The climate of mid-latitude locations
can mean both heating and air-conditioning\index{air-conditioning} are necessary,
potentially increasing the energy required to operate homes in those locations.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Heating and cooling}
\label{sec:heating_and_cooling} \index{households!heating and cooling}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

In most locations,
daily and seasonal temperature variations are larger
than the narrow range of temperatures that provide human comfort.
Average daily temperature variations can be in the range of 12~\degC,
and seasonal variations can be 
on the order of 30~\degC~\cite{Experience-Grand-Rapids:vs}.%
\footnote{
   Example temperature variations are for Grand Rapids, Michigan\index{Grand Rapids, Michigan}, where
   the average daily high temperature in July is 28~\degC{} and in January is 
   $-$2~\degC. 
   Incidentally, the average daily low temperature in January is $-$10~\degC.
}
In contrast, the range of human comfort is between 20~\degC{} and 23~\degC{} (only 3~\degC), 
depending on humidity and clothing\index{clothing}.

Residential heating and cooling reduces the temperature variation
inside a dwelling compared to the outdoors,
providing thermal comfort\index{thermal comfort} to the occupants 
to enable work, play, dining, and entertainment.
Figure~\ref{fig:average_residential_energy} shows that
on average across the U.S.,
thermal comfort\index{thermal comfort}
(that is, space heating\index{space heating} and space cooling\index{space cooling})
is the purpose of 
54.4\% of all residential energy consumption.


%..............................
\paragraph{Building envelope}
\label{sec:building_envelope} \index{building envelope}
%..............................

The purpose of a building envelope\index{building envelope}
(roof, walls, windows\index{window}, and base of a dwelling)
is to shield occupants from outside weather and
to maintain dry and comfortable conditions indoors.
Windows\index{window} are an important part of any building's envelope\index{building envelope}, because
the provide natural illumination.
The ideal building envelope\index{building envelope} would
eliminate both heat loss in the winter and heat gain in the summer via
perfect insulation\index{insulation} and
windows\index{window} that neither conduct heat nor pass thermal radiation\index{thermal radiation}.


%..............................
\paragraph{Heating systems}
\label{sec:heating_systems}
%..............................

Heating systems
(often furnaces\index{furnace}, but also boilers\index{boiler}, heat pumps\index{heat pump}, 
and electric radiant in-floor heating\index{radiant heating})
provide space heating\index{space heating},
usually from an out-of-the-way location in the dwelling, such as the basement.
Heating systems convert a fuel 
(typically natural gas\index{natural gas} or heating oil\index{heating oil} for furnaces and boilers, and
electricity\index{electricity} for heat pumps\index{heat pump})
into heat, 
thereby emitting CO$_2$ into the atmosphere\index{atmosphere}.
The heat is delivered to the dwelling via water or air
circulated by a pump or fan.


%..............................
\paragraph{Air conditioners}
\label{sec:air_conditioners}\index{air conditioners}
%..............................

Air conditioners cool and dehumidify indoor air
to provide thermal comfort\index{thermal comfort}
to building occupants in summer.
Most air conditioners consume electricity\index{electricity} to perform their cooling function, 
causing CO$_2$ to be emitted from grid-connected fossil-fuel power plants. 


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Hygiene}
\label{sec:hygiene}\index{hygiene}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Dwellings consume significant energy and water
for showers\index{shower}, dish washers\index{dish washer},
toilets\index{toilet}, and clothes washers\index{clothes washer} and dryers\index{clothes dryer}.
Collectively, these activities may be categorized as ``hygiene.''\index{hygiene}

Clothes washers and dryers\index{clothes washer}\index{clothes dryer}
consume both water and energy, typically electricity\index{electricity} and natural gas\index{natural gas}.
Burning natural gas\index{natural gas} emits CO$_2$.
When the electricity\index{electricity} for washers\index{clothes washer} and
dryers\index{clothes dryer} comes from fossil-fuel\index{fossil fuels} sources, 
further CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!household} occur.

Hygiene\index{hygiene} is a significant 
cause of energy consumption in the U.S. 
Figure~\ref{fig:average_residential_energy} shows that hygiene\index{hygiene}
(water heating and laundry) demanded 21.9\%
of U.S.\ final energy\index{final energy} consumption in 2015.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Lighting}
\label{sec:lighting}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Indoor lighting\index{indoor lighting} provides illumination for rooms,
typically by consuming electricity\index{fossil-fuel electricity} and emitting 
CO$_2$, if fossil-fuel sources are used.
Indoor lighting\index{indoor lighting} enables work, play, and entertainment
before sunrise and after sunset. 
In many areas of the world, artificial indoor lighting\index{indoor lighting} 
extends the economically active portion of the day
several hours beyond dusk. 

Artificial interior lighting\index{indoor lighting} is a significant 
cause of electricity\index{electricity} consumption in most parts of the world. 
Figure~\ref{fig:average_residential_energy} shows that lighting\index{lighting} accounted for 4.9\%
of U.S.\ final energy\index{final energy} consumption in 2015.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Sustainability challenges in households}\index{sustainability challenges!household}
\label{sec:sustainability_challenges_households}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Energy consumption by households is a significant sustainability challenge.
If the goal is to provide the same energy services\index{energy service} in households
(space heating\index{space heating} and cooling\index{space cooling}, hygiene\index{hygiene}, and lighting\index{lighting}) 
with less energy consumption and fewer environmental impacts, 
efficacy\index{efficacy} plays a big role in becoming more sustainable.
This section discusses sustainability challenges in each 
energy service\index{energy service} discussed above.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Size and location challenges}
\label{sec:size_and_location_challenges}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

A sustainability challenge emerges
from dwelling size.
Families enjoy the comfort and social status of spacious dwellings, 
but large dwellings consume more energy;
see Figure~\ref{fig:EnergyConsAndHomeSize}.
A sustainability challenge associated with dwelling size is
``how can we build small dwellings that are both comfortable and
confer social status?''

Regarding location, cities are sites of large amounts of energy consumption.
But on a per-person basis, cities are energy-efficient
and bring sustainability advantages.
Those advantages accrue from efficiencies that 
accompany high population density\index{population density}.
On the other hand, residents of large cities 
can have long commutes in slow traffic,
thereby eroding the energy benefits of high population density\index{population density}.
Furthermore, high population density\index{population density} is often accompanied by 
negative social dynamics.
(See Chapters~\ref{chap:transportation} and \ref{chap:land_use_urban_planning}
for more discussion of these tradeoffs.)
A sustainability challenge associated with household location\index{sustainability challenges!household location} 
is ``how can we design cities that retain the advantages of urban living
without the drawbacks?''


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Heating and cooling challenges}
\label{sec:heating_cooling_challenges}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

%..............................
\paragraph{Building envelope} 
%..............................

The ideal building envelope\index{building envelope} would
eliminate both heat loss in the winter and heat gain in the summer via
perfect insulation\index{insulation}.
Like walls and roofs, it would be desirable for windows\index{windows} to eliminate
heat loss in the winter and heat gain the summer.
The perfect window\index{window} would provide illumination and
neither conduct heat nor pass thermal radiation\index{thermal radiation}.
But perfect insulation\index{insulation} is not possible, and all windows\index{window} conduct heat and
pass thermal radiation\index{thermal radiation}.
In fact, windows\index{window} are typically worse insulators than walls and roofs,
owing to thin glazing.
Therefore, heating systems and air conditioners\index{air conditioners}
are needed to replace heat lost in winter and remove heat gained in the summer.

The effectiveness of roof and wall insulation\index{insulation}
is quantified by its \textbf{R-value}\index{R-value},
a measure of the resistance to heat transfer through the insulation\index{insulation} material
quantified in units of hr$\cdot$ft$^2\cdot$\degF/BTU.
Higher R-values\index{R-value} mean less heat is transferred.
Large R-values\index{R-value} are achieved with
thicker insulation\index{insulation} constructed from low-thermal-conductivity materials.
Halving the amount of heat that passes means doubling the thickness of the 
insulation\index{insulation}.
Thicker and thicker layers of insulation\index{insulation} are needed to obtain ever-smaller 
fractions of heat transfer reduction. 
Thus, insulation\index{insulation} is subject to diminishing returns in its effectiveness,
and there is a practical and economic optimum level of insulation\index{insulation}.
The \textbf{Energy Star}\index{Energy Star} program recommends levels of roof, wall, and
floor insulation\index{insulation}~\cite{U.S.-Department-of-Energy:aa}.
In Northern US climates, R-values\index{R-value} of 49--60 hr$\cdot$ft$^2\cdot$\degF/BTU are recommended.

The insulative properties of windows\index{window} are quantified by the \textbf{U-factor}\index{U-factor},
which is the inverse of an R-value\index{R-value}.
Typical U-factors\index{U-factor} for windows\index{window} are 0.2--1.2 BTU/hr$\cdot$ft$^2\cdot$\degF.
(Corresponding window\index{window} R-values\index{R-value} are 5--0.83 hr$\cdot$ft$^2\cdot$\degF/BTU.)
Lower U values are more insulative.
Heat gain from solar radiation\index{solar radiation} is quantified by the
\textbf{solar heat gain coefficient (SHGC)}\index{solar heat gain coefficient (SHGC)},
the ratio of solar energy that enters the room to
solar energy incident upon the window\index{window}.
SHGC\index{solar heat gain coefficient (SHGC)} values range from 0 to 1,
and lower SHGC\index{solar heat gain coefficient (SHGC)}
values indicate better insulative properties.
A sustainability challenge associated with the building envelope\index{sustainability challenges!building envelope}
is ``how do we design livable and enjoyable spaces that are 
energy efficient and affordable?''

An interesting tradeoff exists between energy\index{embodied energy} (and CO$_2$\index{embodied carbon})
embodied in structures
and energy consumed in daily life.
A home builder could install extra insulation\index{insulation},
more than local building codes require.
Doing so decreases energy consumption and CO$_2$ emissions \index{CO$_2$ emissions!household}
while the home is in use.
However, the home will embody more energy\index{embodied energy} and carbon\index{embodied carbon},
because many insulation\index{insulation} types
are energy-intensive to manufacture (especially foam). 
A sustainability challenge associated with embodied energy\index{sustainability challenges!embodied energy} 
is ``how do we ensure highly insulative building envelopes\index{building envelope}
with minimal embodied energy?''\index{embodied energy}


%..............................
\paragraph{Heating systems} 
%..............................

Like all energy consumption,
energy consumption for heating and cooling has sustainability implications;
see Chapter~\ref{chap:resource_intensity}.
Furnace efficiency\index{efficiency!furnaces} is quantified as
\textbf{Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency}~(AFUE)\index{Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE)},
the percentage of useful heat output
to fuel energy input,
accounting for transient effects during operation
across the year.
Any heat that leaves the home with the exhaust products 
reduces AFUE\index{Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE)}.
In the absence of heat lost via exhaust, 
the AFUE\index{Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE)} 
rating of a furnace would be 100\%.
AFUE\index{Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE)}
is different from (and lower than) steady-state thermal efficiency.
The American Society of Heating, Refrigerating, and Air-conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE)
\index{American Society of Heating, Refrigerating, and Air-conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE)}
publishes Standard 103,
which specifies how AFUE\index{Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE)}
is to be measured~\cite{ASHRAE:vk}.

All furnaces sold in the U.S.\ have
an AFUE\index{Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE)} rating, and
a minimum AFUE\index{Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE)}
rating of 80\% is required
for gas-fired furnaces.\index{furnaces!gas-fired}
%**** Find a good-quality reference for minimum AFUE of 80\% in the U.S. ****
High-efficiency furnaces recover more heat from exhaust gases,
and some reach AFUE\index{Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE)}
values of 98\% or higher.
A tradeoff exists between efficiency and initial cost.
Models with high AFUE\index{Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE)} are more expensive, initially,
but save money on fuel costs over time.

Heat pumps\index{heat pump} move heat from the cold outdoors to the inside of a home.
Heat pump\index{heat pump} efficiency is quantified by a
\textbf{coefficient of performance (COP)}\index{coefficient of performance (COP)}, 
the ratio of heat delivered to electric energy consumed.
The COP\index{coefficient of performance (COP)} of a heat pump\index{heat pump} varies with outdoor temperature, 
but typical values is 2--3.
Heat pumps\index{heat pump} with higher COP\index{coefficient of performance (COP)}
will be more efficient and cost less to operate, 
even if they have higher purchase price.
A sustainability challenge associated with heating systems\index{sustainability challenges!heating systems}
is ``how can we encourage home builders and home owners to install 
high-efficiency units, despite high initial cost?''


%..............................
\paragraph{Air conditioners} 
%..............................

The energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency} of air conditioners\index{efficiency!air conditioners}
is quantified by the
\textbf{Seasonal Energy Efficiency Ratio (SEER)},\index{seasonal energy efficiency ratio (SEER)}
which is
the ratio of cooling provided (in BTU)
to electricity\index{electricity} consumed (in W$\cdot$hr) throughout the season.
Larger SEER\index{seasonal energy efficiency ratio (SEER)} values indicate higher efficiency
and lower operating costs compared to lower-SEER\index{seasonal energy efficiency ratio (SEER)} air conditioners.

As of 2015, U.S.\ air conditioners must adhere to regionally dependent efficiency standards.
In the Southwest, a minimum SEER\index{seasonal energy efficiency ratio (SEER)} 
value of 14 BTU/W$\cdot$hr is required.
In other parts of the U.S., a minimum SEER\index{seasonal energy efficiency ratio (SEER)}
value of 13 BTU/W$\cdot$hr is mandated.
%**** Find a reference for these SEER numbers. ****
% See email.
Higher efficiency is normally associated with higher purchase price.
Sustainability challenges associated with air conditioners\index{sustainability challenges!air conditioners}
include ``how can we encourage home builders and home owners to install 
high-efficiency units, despite high initial cost?''
and 
``how can we manufacture energy-efficient air-conditioners inexpensively?''


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Hygiene challenges}
\label{sec:hygiene_challenges}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Water heating is the primary source of energy demand for hygiene\index{hygiene} in households.
The efficiency of water heaters\index{water heater} is
quantified by a \textbf{Uniform Energy Factor (UEF)}\index{Uniform Energy Factor (UEF)}, 
a measure of energy required to deliver warm water 
(in the first hour for tank-style water heaters\index{water heater!taks-style} and
as a rate for tankless water heaters\index{water heater!tankless}).
Water heaters\index{water heater} are binned by size (very small, low, medium, and high) and
rated within each bin.
High-efficiency water heaters\index{water heater} tend to be more expensive. 
Thus, a sustainability challenge that emerges from water heating\index{sustainability challenges!water heating} 
is ``how can we encourage home builders and home owners to install 
high-efficiency units, despite high initial cost?''


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Lighting challenges}
\label{sec:lighting_challenges}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Artificial lighting\index{lighting} can be provided by many technologies.
Today, LED lamps\index{LED lamp} 
use one-eighth the energy 
of equivalent \textbf{incandescent lamps}\index{incandescent lamp}.
In addition, LED lamps\index{LED lamp} can last up to 10 times longer than LED lamps\index{LED lamp}.
As a result, operating costs of LED lamps\index{LED lamp} are significantly less than incandescent lamps\index{incandescent lamp}.
Indeed, higher efficiency and longer life reduce total cost of ownership
of LED lamps\index{LED lamp} by nearly two orders of magnitude
compared to incandescent lamps\index{incandescent lamp}.

That said, the purchase price of 
a high-efficiency lamp can be higher than the purchase price of an incandescent lamp\index{incandescent lamp}. 
A sustainability challenge associated with lighting\index{sustainability challenges!lighting}
is ``how can we encourage home owners to replace incandescent lamps\index{incandescent lamp} with LED lamps\index{LED lamp},
despite higher initial cost?''

%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth) \label{page:efficiency_efficacy}
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
Lighting\index{lighting} is one of many areas where 
the effectiveness of a device is better described by a
\textbf{energy service efficacy}\index{energy service efficacy} than by an
energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency}.
Efficiencies are ratios of energies, typically energy output divided by energy input.
In contrast, efficacies are ratios of energy service\index{energy service} output
(not quantified in energy units) to energy input.
Like intensities, efficacies have different units in the numerator and the denominator; 
see Section~\ref{sec:resource_intensity_definitions}.

Lamps can emit both visible\index{visible radiation} and nonvisible radiation\index{nonvisible radiation}.
But (most) people don't buy lamps for their ability to emit nonvisible radiation\index{nonvisible radiation}.
They buy lamps for the energy service\index{energy service} they provide: light!
\textbf{Lighting efficacy}\index{lighting efficacy} is the ratio of visible light output 
(the energy service\index{energy service}, measured in lumens) 
to energy input (measured in W).
A 100-W incandescent lamp\index{incandescent lamp} supplies about 1230~lumens of light 
for a service efficacy\index{energy service efficacy} of 12.3~lumens/W.
A 100-W equivalent LED lamp\index{LED lamp} gives 1200~lumens but consumes only 12~W of electricity\index{electricity},
for a service efficacy\index{energy service efficacy} of 100~lumens/W.
LED lamps\index{LED lamp} are 8 times better than incandescent lamps\index{incandescent lamp} at providing 
their energy service\index{energy service}, lighting\index{lighting}.

The move from energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency} to service efficacy\index{energy service efficacy}
can often reveal sustainability opportunities.
Incandescent and LED lamps\index{LED lamp}
have similar energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency}, because they  
emit nearly as much radiative energy as they consume.
However, most of the radiative energy emitted by an incandescent lamp\index{incandescent lamp}
is in nonvisible wavelengths.
In contrast, most of the radiative energy emitted by an LED lamp\index{LED lamp} is in visible wavelengths.
The lumen counts only visible light output, so 
the service efficacy\index{energy service efficacy} 
(measured in lumens/W, the lighting efficacy\index{lighting efficacy}) 
penalizes incandescent lamps\index{incandescent lamp} 
for emitting most of their energy in nonvisible wavelengths.
(See \citet{Heun:2020aa} for details.)
The service efficacy\index{energy service efficacy}
favors LED lamps\index{LED lamp}, because they emit most of their energy in visible wavelengths.
While an energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency} metric would say that
incandescent\index{incandescent lamp} and
LED lamps\index{LED lamp} are similarly efficient, 
the lumen/W lighting efficacy\index{lighting efficacy} metric correctly suggests 
that LED lamps\index{LED lamp} are far superior to incandescent lamps\index{incandescent lamp}
for the task of converting electricity\index{electricity} to visible light.
When available, service efficacies are preferred over energy efficiencies, 
because they can point toward sustainability benefits.
\end{mcframe}


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Sustainability transitions in households}
\label{sec:sustainability_transitions_households}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

In the areas discussed above
(size and location, heating\index{space heating} and cooling\index{space cooling}, 
hygiene\index{hygiene}, and lighting), 
sustainability transitions take the form of 
obtaining the same energy services\index{energy service}
with less resources consumption, especially energy. 
As such, the household sustainability transitions discussed below
will have the effect of reducing the resource intensity of the economy
(\:\!\REp{} for the prime example of energy and CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions}).


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Size and location transitions}
\label{sec:size_location_transitions}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

%..............................
\paragraph{Size} 
%..............................

Figure~\ref{fig:NewHousingSize} shows that the average size of new housing starts
rose from 1970 to 2014
but has been falling since. 
At the level of the average single home, 
the recent trend is in the direction of sustainable housing, 
as Figure~\ref{fig:EnergyConsAndHomeSize} shows that 
energy consumption per home would be expected to fall as floor size decreases.
However, at the level of the entire country (U.S.), 
the increase in number of new homes
indicates that energy consumption in the housing stock of the U.S.\ is unlikely 
to fall in the near future. 
Every new home adds to the energy consumed by homes in the U.S.
That is, efficiency gains will be overtaken by the sheer number of new homes.


%..............................
\paragraph{Location} 
%..............................

Figure~\ref{fig:urbanization} shows the percentage of world population
living in urban areas.
The transition to urban living is proceeding quickly for many reasons.
A primary factor is that people move from rural areas to cities 
in search of employment. 
That is, urbanization is happening for reasons of social sustainability\index{social sustainability}
(employment and human well-being)
rather than reasons of environmental sustainability\index{environmental sustainability}.
The only question is whether the location transition 
will be managed in an environmentally sustainable direction.

