%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Heating and cooling transition}
\label{sec:heating_cooling_transition}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

There are several ways to transition to more sustainable heating and cooling in households.
First, in-floor radiant heating\index{radiant heating} is often considered more comfortable than 
forced air, allowing thermostats\index{thermostat} to be set lower,
thereby consuming less energy for the same level of comfort.
(This is an example of the benefit 
of focusing on energy service efficacy\index{energy service efficacy},
in this case thermal comfort\index{thermal comfort} per BTU,
instead of energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency};
see page~\pageref{page:efficiency_efficacy}.)

Second, \textbf{programmable thermostats}\index{thermostat!programmable}
can be used to save energy on heating and cooling 
for households with regular schedules.
\textbf{Remote-control thermostats}\index{thermostat!remote-control} are
beneficial for reducing heating and cooling
energy consumption when schedules deviate from programmed timetables.

Third, high-efficiency heating and cooling systems
can provide the same thermal comfort\index{thermal comfort}
with less energy consumed.
Increased residential heating and cooling 
efficiency\index{efficiency!heating and cooling!residential}
(that is, providing the same comfort with less energy) 
can be obtained
by improving the building envelope\index{building envelope} or
by improving the efficiency of heating and air-conditioning\index{air-conditioning}.
Standards that mandate high efficiency
are one way to ensure that efficiency of heating and cooling systems
improves in the stock of housing. 


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Hygiene transition}
\label{sec:hygiene_transition}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

To minimize environmental impacts of showering\index{shower} and dish washing\index{dish washer},
low-flow showerheads\index{low-flow showerhead} and faucets\index{low-flow faucet}
can be installed.
Low-flow showerheads\index{low-flow showerhead} and faucets\index{low-flow faucet}
provide the obvious benefit of
reducing water bills.
Furthermore, sewerage costs are reduced, because 
low-flow showerheads\index{low-flow showerhead} and faucets\index{low-flow faucet}
decrease the amount of gray water entering the sewer system (with ``downstream''
energy and cost savings).
If less water is consumed for cooking and bathing,
energy consumption and CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!household} are reduced.
Furthermore, some systems can reuse gray water for irrigation\index{irrigation} 
and toilet\index{toilet} flushing,
thereby reducing clean water demand.

Saving water and energy in dish washing\index{dish washer} can be accomplished by purchasing a
high-efficiency \textbf{automatic dishwasher}\index{dishwasher}.
The Energy Star\index{Energy Star} program provides 
information about energy-saving dishwashers\index{dishwasher}~\cite{U.S.-Department-of-Energy:vn}.
% "According to a recent study by detergent brand Cascade, it takes the average 
% person about 15 seconds to hand-wash a dish. During that time, the sink uses 
% half a gallon of water (a typical faucet spouts four gallons of water every two 
% minutes). By comparison, an Energy Star-certified dishwasher uses less than four
% gallons per cycle, which means running a load with as few as eight dishes can 
% actually save water."
% https://www.bhg.com/kitchen/appliances/dishwasher-save-water/
% Cascade press release: https://news.pg.com/news-releases/news-details/2020/Cascade-Comes-Clean-About-Dishwashing-Habit/default.aspx
%% Perhaps a project to verify their "15 seconds per dish" finding.

To save water consumed by toilets\index{toilets},
displacement and dual-flush systems are recommended.
A displacement system occupies water volume in the tank,
reducing the amount of water used for each flush.
Dual-flush systems provide half- and full-flushes
for disposal of liquids and solids, respectively.

At a larger scale, reduced water consumption means 
less water to treat and distribute and 
less sewage to process.
Lower volumes of treatment, distribution, and sewage
will mean cost and energy savings for municipalities and 
could mean smaller plants and public works.

Purchasing washers\index{clothes washer} and dryers\index{clothes dryer} 
with Energy Star\index{Energy Star} ratings can reduce
energy and water consumption by 25\% and 33\%,
respectively~\cite{U.S.-Department-of-Energy:tc, U.S.-Department-of-Energy:vd}.
Energy can be saved by washing clothes\index{clothing} less frequently,
using a cold-water cycle, and line drying clothes\index{clothing}.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Lighting transition}
\label{sec:lighting_transition}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

After Edison's\index{Edison, Thomas} invention of the electric light\index{electric lamp},
filament-based incandescent lighting technology\index{incandescent lamp}
dominated household lighting\index{lighting}.
However, in recent years,
Compact Fluorescent Lights (CFLs)\index{CFL lamp} and
Light-Emitting Diode (LED) lamps\index{LED lamp} have revolutionized
the lighting\index{lighting} industry and improved lighting efficacy\index{lighting efficacy} significantly.

In the U.S., a transition to LED lamps\index{LED lamp} is well underway,
with incandescent\index{incandescent lamp} and CFL lamps\index{CFL lamp} usually unavailable in stores.
The lighting\index{lighting} transition in the U.S.\ has been hastened
by point-of-purchase subsidies for LED lamps\index{LED lamp}
and by in-home energy-efficiency audits offered by utilities.

Of course, the least expensive lamp is the one you don't need to use.
Building design techniques such as \textbf{light harvesting}\index{light harvesting}
use natural light to reduce the need for artificial indoor lighting\index{lighting}.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Summary}
\label{sec:household_summary}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

This chapter identified many sustainability challenges that pertain to dwellings
and decisions made by ordinary people in their homes and apartments.
Energy and material consumption decisions by household members
drives sustainability in the home. 
Key areas of decision making include
size and location, 
heating\index{space heating} and cooling\index{space cooling},
hygiene\index{hygiene}, and
lighting\index{lighting}, 
because many homeowners have agency in these areas of everyday life.

This chapter illustrates two fundamental tradeoffs for sustainability.
The first tradeoff is initial cost (also called capital expense) versus operating cost.
Models or options that are more energy efficient also tend to cost more for the initial purchase. 
A larger initial investment pays back by reducing ongoing expenses.
Often the higher initial cost is the result of higher energy and/or material inputs
required to manufacture the more efficient option.
The second kind of tradeoff is between well-being or affluence and cost. 
Turning the thermostat\index{thermostat} down means your home is less comfortable, which
means that you are not as well off (not as happy). 
On the other hand, turning the thermostat\index{thermostat} down 
saves money, energy, and CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!household}.
For both of these kinds of tradeoffs, price is the determiner as to how the tradeoff
plays out. 
Changing society-wide behavior means manipulating prices---of goods, of energy, or both.

Chapter~\ref{chap:personal_action} provides additional concrete suggestions
for making homes and apartments more sustainable.


