\begin{questions}

\item This chapter covered five important aspects of household sustainability
      (size, location, heating\index{space heating} and cooling\index{space cooling}, 
      hygiene\index{hygiene}, and lighting\index{lighting}).
      Which is most important and why?
      What additional areas of household living are important
      from a sustainability point of view?
      
\item What ways can you imagine to re-use or recycle water in a home
      to get closer to a circular economy\index{circular economy}?

\item \label{question:household_policies} Here are several household-related sustainability policies:
   \begin{enumerate}
      \item require everyone to live in cities (to reduce commuting distances), 
      \item outlaw clothes washers\index{clothes washer} that use hot water (to save CO$_2$ emissions 
            from water heating\index{CO$_2$ emissions!water heating}),
      \item outlaw automatic dishwashers\index{dishwasher} (to reduce energy consumption for water heating),
      \item require all clothes washing\index{clothes washer}
            to be done at laundromats\index{laundromat} (to reduce embodied energy\index{embodied energy}
            of clothes washers\index{clothes washer} in every home),
      \item require all homes to undergo an energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency}
            retrofit before going on the market to be sold
            (to improve energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency} of the housing stock),
      \item require all homes to generate solar electricity\index{solar electricity} onsite (to move quickly to a renewable future), and
      \item prohibit clothing\index{clothing} made from synthetic fibers
            (to minimize microplastic pollution\index{pollution!microplastic}).
   \end{enumerate}
      Which of these policies would you welcome? 
      Which would you reject?
      Why?
      
\item Where should you invest in energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency} in your home or apartment?

\item Why is nearly every suburban homeowner in the northern U.S.\
      also a Kentucky bluegrass\index{Kentucky bluegrass} farmer?
      What are the benefits and drawbacks of this arrangement? 
      What are the sustainability implications of this arrangement?
      
\item What are the pros and cons of gardening? Of lawn care? Think, at least,
      in terms of species diversity, emissions/pollution\index{pollution}, resource use, affluence,
      and social implications.
      (See Section~\ref{sec:personal_land_use} for more on lawn care.)
      
\item What are ways to increase people per acre and/or people per dwelling?
      In what ways are these the same and how are they different?
      Do you think that dwellings that increase either of these metrics should 
      be incentivized? Why or why not? What are your reasons?
      
\item Negative externalities\index{negative externality} are costs borne by those 
      who do not receive the benefits of an activity. 
      For example, burning natural gas\index{natural gas} to heat a home releases CO$_2$
      (which harms everyone). 
      Improving a home's energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency}
      improves the well being of everyone
      by reducing the costs of these negative externalities\index{negative externality}. 
      Thus, ``all'' of us stand to benefit from energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency}. 
      What are some ways to provide resources for deep energy retrofits for those 
      who otherwise couldn't afford to do so?
      What might be the (perhaps unforeseen) consequences or ramifications of 
      such a plan? 
      How could those ``side effects'' be mitigated?
      
\item Examine your use of in-home appliances and resources. 
      Do you leave lights on? 
      Leave the water running when you brush your teeth? 
      Wash dishes by hand? 
      Leave computers or entertainment systems in ``standby'' mode when not in use,
      consuming ``phantom,''\index{phantom power} ``vampire,''\index{vampire power} 
      or standby power\index{standby power}? 
      Why do you do these things?
      Does your home have a second (or third) refrigerator\index{refrigerator} or freezer\index{freezer}?
      Why?
      What would it take for you to change your behavior?
      
\item Notice that biomass\index{biomass} heating (for example, firewood\index{firewood}) is not included in 
      Figure~\ref{fig:EnergyConsAndHomeSize}. However, 
      RECS\index{Residential Energy Consumption Survey (RECS)}
      Table CE 7.2 reports that wood heated\index{wood heating} 12.5 million housing units in
      2015 (10.6\% of all housing units) and was 5.6\% of all BTUs used for
      heating. 
      (For around 60\% of housing units wood\index{wood heating} is the main source of heat;
      for the other 40\% it's secondary.)
      Wood heating\index{wood heating} can be carbon neutral\index{carbon neutral}. 
      However, wood heating\index{wood heating} isn't exactly sustainable. 
      It is sustainable only if not everyone does it. 
      If everyone heated with wood\index{wood heating},
      one result would be massive deforestation\index{deforestation}.
      Another might be greatly increased air pollution\index{pollution!air} (in the form of soot).
      Should the use of wood heating\index{wood heating} be expanded or contracted? 
      Who gets to (or has to) heat with wood\index{wood heating} and what emissions should be permitted?
      How should such questions be decided?
      What other considerations go into wood heating\index{wood heating}? 
      For example, who has access to forest lands? How much does wood cost?
      What labor\index{labor} is required to obtain and use wood for heat?\index{wood heating}
      
\item Figure~\ref{fig:EnergyConsAndHomeSize} also excludes ``district steam''\index{district steam heating}
      and solar thermal heat\index{solar thermal heating} sources.
      Should such sources be promoted for sustainability? 
      What considerations affect their more widespread adoption?
      
\item This chapter discussed energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency} measures 
      for many of the categories featured in Figure \ref{fig:average_residential_energy}, 
      such as AFUE\index{Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE)},
      SEER\index{seasonal energy efficiency ratio (SEER)}, and
      Energy Star\index{Energy Star} 
      labels. 
      However, some categories of appliances do not have an efficiency rating. 
      What are some appliances that could be rated that are not?
      (See, for instance, \href{https://www.energystar.gov/productfinder/}
      {www.energystar.gov/productfinder}.)
      Vacuum cleaners\index{vacuum cleaner}, for example, are difficult to rate, 
      in part, because defining how well they do their job (that is, the  
      ``numerator'' of a service efficacy metric) is difficult to define.
      (See the Energy Star\index{Energy Star} \emph{Market and Industry Scoping Report
      on Vacuum Cleaners\index{vacuum cleaners}}, November 2011.)
      
\item Should product longevity be factored into consumer-oriented energy 
      efficiency\index{energy efficiency} ratings? 
      If so, how? 
      Do you think a vacuum cleaner\index{vacuum cleaner} that lasts 10 years is better
      than a vacuum cleaner\index{vacuum cleaner} that lasts only 5 years?
      Is it more energy efficient? In what sense?
      Under what conditions or assumptions?
      
\item Should consumer appliances and household goods be required to contribute 
      to a circular economy\index{circular economy}?
      If so, under what conditions or which appliances? 
      Should electronics recycling\index{recycling} be mandatory?
      
\item One thing that you can do to make your housing unit more energy efficient
      is to eat every meal at a restaurant. Think of all energy you will save!
      No need for freezers, refrigeration, cooking, or dish washing\index{dish washer}. 
      Figure~\ref{fig:average_residential_energy} shows these categories
      are 10.4\% of the energy use by an average household.
      What is wrong with this analysis?
      Under what circumstances could it be correct?
      Are there opportunities to improve sustainability by outsourcing other 
      common tasks like laundry, or house cleaning? If so, what are they?
      
\item Consider detached homes compared to townhouses 
      (multilevel dwellings connected to neighboring dwellings).
      What are the advantages and disadvantages of each?
      Which will be more energy efficient? Why?
      Which would you rather call ``home?''
      What are other factors involved in where you decide to live, 
      now or in the future?
      What are the assumptions, values, and tradeoffs that lead to your decision?
      For you, what factors would move the tradeoffs in the other direction?
      
\item Consider the sustainability challenges associated with old and new homes.
      For old homes, what does it take to make them more energy efficient? 
      Be sure to think about historic preservation value and technology 
      appropriate for old structures.
      For new homes, what does it take to implement standards for 
      higher system efficiencies and enhanced insulation\index{insulation}?
      You might want to investigate the passive house movement, 
      the living building challenge, net zero homes, and 
      Joe Lstiburek\index{Lstiburek, Joeseph} (Section~\ref{sec:stories_individual_actions}).
      Given a fixed amount of money, 
      do you suppose there is more sustainability impact 
      in improving old homes or investing in new construction?

\end{questions}


